TY  - JOUR
T1  - Asset Pricing with Downside Liquidity Risks
AU  - Anthonisz, Sean A.
AU  - Putniņš, Tālis J.
Y1  - 2016/05/31
PY  - 2016
DA  - 2017/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.2016.2438
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.2016.2438
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 2549
EP  - 2572
VL  - 63
IS  - 8
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - We develop a parsimonious liquidity-adjusted downside capital asset pricing model to investigate whether phenomena such as downward liquidity spirals and flights to liquidity impact expected asset returns. We find strong empirical support for the model. Downside liquidity risk (sensitivity of stock liquidity to negative market returns) has an economically meaningful return premium that is 10 times larger than its symmetric analogue. The expected liquidity level and downside market risk are also associated with meaningful return premiums. Downside liquidity risk and its associated premium are higher during periods of low marketwide liquidity and for stocks that are relatively small, illiquid, volatile, and have high book-to-market ratios. These results are consistent with investors requiring compensation for holding assets susceptible to adverse liquidity phenomena. Our findings suggest that mitigation of downside liquidity risk can lower firms? cost of capital. This paper was accepted by Lauren Cohen, finance.
AB  - We develop a parsimonious liquidity-adjusted downside capital asset pricing model to investigate whether phenomena such as downward liquidity spirals and flights to liquidity impact expected asset returns. We find strong empirical support for the model. Downside liquidity risk (sensitivity of stock liquidity to negative market returns) has an economically meaningful return premium that is 10 times larger than its symmetric analogue. The expected liquidity level and downside market risk are also associated with meaningful return premiums. Downside liquidity risk and its associated premium are higher during periods of low marketwide liquidity and for stocks that are relatively small, illiquid, volatile, and have high book-to-market ratios. These results are consistent with investors requiring compensation for holding assets susceptible to adverse liquidity phenomena. Our findings suggest that mitigation of downside liquidity risk can lower firms? cost of capital. This paper was accepted by Lauren Cohen, finance.
SN  - 0025-1909
M3  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.2016.2438
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1287/mnsc.2016.2438
Y2  - 2024/03/29
